Task: How can I create a single function in Rust that accepts both sync fn and async fn?

 <p>I’m building a small web server in Rust and I want the server’s <code>add_route</code> method to accept both synchronous and asynchronous handlers ergonomically.</p>
<p><strong>Goal:</strong> allow end-users to write code as simple as:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>// user/main.rs (example)
fn sync_handler(_req: &amp;Request) -&gt; Response { /* ... */ }
async fn async_handler(_req: &amp;Request) -&gt; Response { /* ... */ }

fn main() {
  let mut server = Server::new();

  // The same call should work for both kinds of functions
  server.add_route(&quot;/sync&quot;, sync_handler);
  server.add_route(&quot;/async&quot;, async_handler);
}
</code></pre>
<p>To achieve this, I’m trying to unify both kinds of functions into a single stored type (<code>Handler</code>) by converting them to a function that returns a <code>BoxFuture</code>.</p>
<p>Here is a simplified version of my library-side implementation using the standard <code>From</code> trait:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>// code: lib.rs (library side)
use std::future::Future;
use std::sync::Arc;
use futures::future::BoxFuture;

// Minimal structs for illustration
pub struct Request;
pub struct Response;

// Unified stored type: (&amp;Request) -&gt; BoxFuture&lt;Response&gt;
type HandlerFn =
  dyn for&lt;'a&gt; Fn(&amp;'a Request) -&gt; BoxFuture&lt;'a, Response&gt; + Send + Sync + 'static;

pub struct Handler(Arc&lt;HandlerFn&gt;);

// Conversion for an `async` handler: Fn(&amp;Request) -&gt; impl Future&lt;Output = Response&gt;
impl&lt;F, Fut&gt; From&lt;F&gt; for Handler
where
  F: for&lt;'a&gt; Fn(&amp;'a Request) -&gt; Fut + Send + Sync + 'static,
  for&lt;'a&gt; Fut: Future&lt;Output = Response&gt; + Send + 'a,
{
  fn from(f: F) -&gt; Self {
    Handler(Arc::new(move |req| Box::pin(f(req))))
  }
}

// Conversion for a `sync` handler: Fn(&amp;Request) -&gt; Response
impl&lt;F&gt; From&lt;F&gt; for Handler
where
  F: for&lt;'a&gt; Fn(&amp;'a Request) -&gt; Response + Send + Sync + 'static,
{
  fn from(f: F) -&gt; Self {
    Handler(Arc::new(move |req| Box::pin(async move { f(req) })))
  }
}

// Simplified server
pub struct Server { /* ... */ }

impl Server {
  pub fn new() -&gt; Self { /* ... */ Self { /* ... */ } }

  pub fn add_route&lt;F&gt;(&amp;mut self, _path: &amp;str, f: F)
  where
    Handler: From&lt;F&gt;,
  {
    let _handler = Handler::from(f);
    // store the handler ...
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Problem:</strong></p>
<p>When compiling, the call with the sync handler works, but the call with the async handler fails with HRTB/opaque <code>impl Future</code> mismatch:</p>
<pre><code>error: one type is more general than the other
  --&gt; src/main.rs:10:5
   |
10 |     server.add_route(&quot;/async&quot;, async_handler);
   |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
   |
   = note: expected opaque type `impl for&lt;'a&gt; Future&lt;Output = Response&gt;`
              found opaque type `impl Future&lt;Output = Response&gt;`
</code></pre>
<p>I understand this is a tricky Rust limitation involving higher-ranked trait bounds and opaque <code>impl Future</code> types. My question is:</p>
<ul>
<li>Is there a way to structure my <code>impl From&lt;F&gt;</code> bounds or the <code>add_route</code> signature so that this compiles and I can offer that simple API?</li>
<li>If that simple API is not possible, is there any other approach that is easy on the user?</li>
</ul>


